metadata.name: All Fold: Sketch #130
metadata.description:
'All Fold: Sketch' is a generative system intended to celebrate the writing and artwork that can only be found in the pages of a sketchbook. The project itself is much like a sketch, and attempts to represent the spirit of a work-in-progress.

The fold is included as a reminder that there is always another page.

In the context of the market, the pricing of this project is intended to offer an enjoyable minting experience, while giving the opportunity to contribute to important charities.

- 60% of any primary sales will be split between "Girls Who Code" and "Cure Parkinson's"
- 60% of any royalties will be split between "Girls Who Code" and "Cure Parkinson's"

The aesthetics of this project were directly inspired by the works of Gunta Stölzl, Anni Albers, Gertrud Arndt, Kenneth Martin, and Josef Albers.

Created by Eric Davidson. 2023.

metadata.name: Mosaic #166
metadata.description:
---
Notes:
- Click to pause/unpause
- The aspect ratio is fixed 1:1 because of the way the grid and movements are generated to make sure they're the same on all screens. 
---
Description:
An 80X80 grid of tiles are scrambled, shuffled, shifted, streamed, transported,
conveyed, moved, deposited. 

There are 15 initial tile states and 5 color palettes. A set of 12 unique motion patterns
are generated for each piece. 
---
Acknowledgements:
This piece is inspired by Kim Asendorf, whose pixel-level algorithms I'm
transfixed by, and Ksawery Komputery, whose algorithmic tile-works I'm crazy
about. 
---
Made by Sam Tsao (@sam___tsao) with P5.js 
December 2021, Germany

metadata.name: Bone Shell #11
metadata.description:
A collection of geometric abstractions with architectural imagination.

Bone-Shell continues to exploit the infinite potential of simple geometries, it reveals a new vocabulary of colors and positive-negative relationships while returning to an earlier emotional intensity. The striking noisy black background of artworks lends brilliance to the colors and makes both them and the forms vibrate. This creates a mood and provides relief for the colors and forms placed against it.

Generative artwork by KINTSUGI BOI (@kintsugi_boi)

metadata.name: Lost Twins #225
metadata.description:
Individually, the mints of this token are very simple. Each mint generates half of two cube forms, and each half is assigned random hues (in multiples of 10, from 0 to 360). Collectively as a project, this token challenges the approach of looking for "rarities" in a new way. How the cubes are rendered leaves the possibility for multiple mints to potentially join up on the sides with colors that perfect match each other. Will you find your lost twin?

Made in p5js
Created November 2021
Artist: @Yazid

metadata.name: Hatchbeats #5
metadata.description:
Hatchbeats are endless beat generators.

After a Hatchbeat loads, click once to start the beat, and click again to hatch it. Once hatched, clicking will toggle the audio.

Hatchbeats are not drum loops. Each Hatchbeat continuously improvises bars based on its prototype. Prototypes are patterns of hits where each hit has some probability of happening in any bar. There are 3 high hat prototypes and 4 kick/snare prototypes.

Each Hatchbeat selects high hat, kick, and snare sounds from 76 possible samples which have 8736 combinations. The playback rates of these samples are modified for each Hatchbeat to create a virtually infinite number of drum kits.

Hatchbeat tempos range from 140 bpm to 200 bpm and come in several colors.

metadata.name: primordial soup #23
metadata.description:
1024 kinematic automata that imitate living organisms, leaving behind a trace of paint before going extinct. Blotches of paint are deposited by these nodes that attract and repulse each other according to rules based on their color and size.

Short description of features:
- mood: the palette
- tone: the noisiness
- flow: the number of neighbors affecting each node
- brow: the brush size
- delirium: brush modifier
- distancing: kinetic rule modifier

Each feature is equally likely - rarity is in the eye of the beholder.

@balidani
